Well, that means the problem is the file itself, not those test cases. Mind that it's nothing unusual for test cases to take same or greater number of lines as the implementation itself.

I would suggest to make attempts on dividing the files instead. Server chunk is a low hanging fruit to evict. 
Chunk position and block position is a material for another file, alongside some clean up in coordinate notation we use. 
Neighbor structure has stopped being chunk only construct long ago, it could be a separate file too. 
At that point there should be a folder with a bunch of files.
Suddenly having double the code volume for each of those is not that scary.

Yes, more code is more maintenance, but less code doesn't always equal less maintenance. Tests verify that what was true about your code back when you wrote it remains true over time. Tests document your code by showing how to use it and what to expect. This is a documentation that never silently goes obsolete. Tests help with refactoring. They are a list of important conditions that have to be true about your code.

---

Technically we could move test cases to mirrored file structure, but I admit I like having those tests nearby. *They are great documentation for verifying if I read the code right.* Additionally this is basically hiding the problem, not solving it. Cubyz source files frequently consolidate a lot of standalone functionality. That functionality would do perfectly fine as separate files.

