It is reasonable to disallow this, as there is system wide convention that dots are separators for file extensions. What would be the use case for this that can not be replaced by using `-` or `_`? These are just names, separators between words are arbitrary. Moreover, I am worried about the fact that we allow whitespace in IDs which means that commands which take IDs as parameters must account for that during parameter parsing. This is a lot of freedom, a lot of edge cases, not a lot of use cases for this freedom. I think it would be reasonable to constrain block names to match regex `[a-zA-Z0-9-_]+`, this makes it infinitely easier to reason about how they should be parsed. I want to also point out that having block IDs case sensitive as they are right now might be an issue while transferring from Windows to Unix OS, as `addon:Stone` and `addon:stone` behave differently on those.

